Kiess Wall Command requires current field data on the Cinderteeth foothills wildlife population before it can finalize the threat classification for the mountain entry zone. Ashrunner packs have been disrupting scout approach lines, mountain bears have moved into the saddle approaches at unusual density, and thermal spring basilisks are making the lower hot-spring corridors impassable. Engage one of each to give Wall Command baseline behavior data for the entry zone classification update.
The wildlife verification report is complete and Kiess Wall Command has updated the Cinderteeth entry zone classification from unassessed to documented-wildlife-active. The mountain bear density data was the most significant finding: the population has shifted from mineral-lick zones into the saddle approaches, which Wall Command analysts believe is a response to something pushing them out of their traditional territory farther up the range. The entry zone threat classification now includes a footnote about upstream pressure.
